Your family lived on the outskirts of civilisation, in a 
tiny hamlet composed of you, your immediate family, and a 
number of cousins, uncles, aunts, nephews, nieces and other 
close relations. While much of life was spent tilling 
infertile fields and herding flocks of goat or sheep, your 
family were also keen hunters. Since you could walk, you 
accompanied your father and brothers as they hunted, whether 
for small game such as stoats and marmots, or larger prey 
like deer and boar. 

You grew knowledgeable in all aspects of the hunt, from 
first spotting the tracks of an animal to preparing its 
meat and hide for sale in town. The various tools of the 
hunt are familiar to you, and you have chosen a particular 
method in taking down prey. Whilst not trained to hold your 
own in an open battle, you are skilled in ways that warriors 
are not, and well adapted to prosper in the wilderness of 
Beleriand.

Soldier

You grew up in a small village, or perhaps a sleepy trade town, for many years just another peasant child. In your teen years you were given up, maybe voluntarily or maybe not, as part of the Tithe. You entered in to the service on an Elvish Lord, helping maintaing the Siege of Angband in one of the watch towers constructed around the forboding Iron Mountains.

Serving as a soldier along side many other young humans, you were given rudimentary training in the skills of battle, and spent several long years marching across the empty grasslands of Ard-galen. In the peace times, you took the opportunity to learn a skill or two, as well as become familiar with Quenya, the tongue of your Elvish leaders. You also took part in a battle or two against the foul orcs from the north, and perhaps were injured or saw friends die. Now, you have been released from the Tithe, your service complete, and are now left to make your own way in Beleriand.

Outcast

Whatever your life may have been before becoming an outcast, it was meaningless the instant you were discovered. Your former friends helped chase you out from your hamlet, village or town, and your family disowned you. Whatever it was you did, it was enough to earn you an informal banishment from the place you used to call home.

Since that time, you have been living as an outcast in the wilds of Beleriand, occasionally on your own, at other times teaming up with other dregs of humanity. You have had to fend for yourself, nearly freezing and starving every winter, and desperately bartering and begging for food in summer. Despite this, you have none-the-less accquired an interesting set of talents: it is merely a shame that the trees and rocks hold no appreciation for them.

